    "Personally, he maintained close intellectual friendships with, among others, leader of the so-called second Vienna School of art history, <a href=\"/schlosserj\">Julius Alwin von Schlosser</a>, who translated his Baroque essays into German, as well as with <a href=\"/venturia\">Adolfo Venturi</a>, his son, <a href=\"/venturil\">Lionello Venturi</a> and <a href=\"/paner\">Roberto Pane</a>; his writing was crucial to the work of many other art historians, including <a href=\"/argang\">Giulio Carlo Argan</a>, <a href=\"/ragghiantic\">Carlo Ludovico Ragghianti</a> and <a href=\"/longhir\">Roberto Longhi</a>.": []
